Kernel-isolation A: k=5 polyphase (L=600, pk_k5) with k=2's bigger kernels (31, 8, 8) instead of the apr25 RF-matched (13, 3, 4). RF = 311 sub-samples × 5 ms = 1555 raw-ms (vs baseline 622 raw-ms — 2.5× more temporal context). Default channels (64/128/256). Tests whether the apr25 k=5 collapse (+0.087) was caused by kernel-shrinking from the RF-match constraint. R² near +0.30+ → architectural cramping was the dominant cause; with proper kernels k=5 works. R² near +0.10 → polyphase decimation at 5× hurts beyond architecture (time-domain feature granularity).